Nicola Lener, the Head of Delegation for the Italian Presidency of the G7, attended the last meeting yesterday of the Committee for the Order and Security held by the Prefect of Naples, Michele Di Bari. The island in these weeks resumes life after the winter break: have just reopened the hotels, as well as the shops of the great luxury signatures, all present in the island-icon of 'bel live' Italian. Tourists, who already crowd the streets, distrino apparent affanno in spite of the safety measures: the place where the ministerial meeting will take place is the Grand Hotel Quisisana, a stone's throw from the 'piazzetta', the island's lounge; and the accesses are discreetly supervised. Just a few dozen meters away, the 'media center' will be hosting the 250 accredited journalists. Even the islanders do not seem annoyed: they have a natural wisdom and have taken with philosophy the hustle and bustle of this 'three days'. Many of the shops carry the plaque, 'Capri da' welcome to the G7 summit.' And as a local hotelier says, "It has to pass" 'feed'. >
<h2> The words of Tajani</h2>
"In an international scenario characterized by strong tensions, the Italian G7 has the task of working for peace": In a note, the Foreign Minister, Antonio Tajani, who today welcomes the delegations of the 7 most industrialized countries in the world (Usa, Canada, Japan, Germany, Great Britain and France) for the Group's Foreign Minister that begins today in Capri.
